      "sv": {
        "purpose": "Att utvärdera och registrera en självskattning av depressiva symtom hos patienter, i enlighet med Quick Inventory of Depressive Symptomology (QIDS).",
        "keywords": [
          "QIDS",
          "depression",
          "MDD",
          "DSM"
        ],
        "use": "QIDS kan användas av såväl patienter själva som av anhöriga för självskattning och dokumentation av depressiva symtom över tid. \n\nDe sexton frågorna utgår från nio olika områden relaterade till depression inkluderande sömnsvårigheter, sinnesstämning, aptit, viktförändring, egenvärde/självuppfattning, beslutsförmåga, suicidala tankar, psykomotorisk funktion, intresse av andra människor samt energinivå. Respektive fråga graderas med 0-4p.\n\nTotala poängen uppgår till maximalt 27p. För fråga 1-4, 6-9, 15-16 tas endast högst graderade svaret med i beräkningen. Detta gör att endast nio frågor bidrar till totala poängsumman. \n\nResultat tolkas enligt:\n    \n    ≤5 indikerar att depression ej föreligger\n    6-10 indikerar förekomst av mild depression\n    11-15 indikerar förekomst av måttlig depression\n    16-20 indikerar förekomst av allvarlig/svår depression\n    ≥ 21p indikerar mycket svår depression",
        "misuse": "Bör ej användas isolerat utan är avsedd att användas i kombination med psykiatrisk bedömning och övriga adekvata resurser.",
        "copyright": "© Cambio Healthcare Systems"
      },
      "en": {
        "purpose": "A self-reported method to quantify depressive symptoms from patients across 16 multiple choice questions, which relate to 9 depression symptoms.",
        "keywords": [
          "QIDS",
          "depression",
          "MDD",
          "DSM"
        ],
        "use": "The QIDS (Quick Inventory of Depressive Symptomology) helps those patients whom either see themselves or whom may be seen by others as being depressed using a self-assessment method of scoring, mapping the extent of their feelings of depression over a 4 point scale and across 16 questions. \n\nThese questions relate to 9 depression symptoms regarding sleep patterns, mood, appetite, weight fluctuations, worth, decision-making, suicidal thoughts, speed of thinking/gesturing/speaking, interest in other people and energy level.\n\nThe scoring system works, for the most part, in the usual way: by adding the individual scores as recorded by the patient for each question who fills it in as normal. However, for questions 1-4, 6-9, 15 and 16, only the highest score is recorded and added to the running total. Thus creating only 1 score for each of the 9 depression symptoms as described above. \n\nThe score values span from 0 to 3 at each response, giving a max total score of 27 (3 multiplied by 9).\n\nScore Interpretation is based on 5 grades of severity:\n\nScore 0-5 - No Depression Likely\nScore 6-10 - Indicates Mild Depression\nScore 11-15 - Indicates Moderate Depression\nScore 16-20 - Indicates Severe Depression\nScore ≥ 21 - Indicates Very Severe Depression",
        "misuse": "Do not use in isolation of supporting psychiatric assessment and without the provision of other supporting resources as needed.",
        "copyright": "© Cambio Healthcare Systems"
      }
    },
    "otherDetails": {
      "references": "Ref. 1: Rush AJ, Giles DE, Schlesser MA, Fulton CL, Weissenburger JE, Burns CT. The Inventory of Depressive Symptomatology (IDS): Preliminary findings. Psychiatry Research. 1986; 18:65-87. \n\nRef. 2: Rush AJ, Trivedi MH, Ibrahim HM, Carmody TJ, Arnow B, Klein DN, Markowitz JC, Ninan PT, Kornstein S, Manber R, Thase ME, Kocsis JH, Keller MB. The 16-item Quick Inventory of Depressive Symptomatology (QIDS) Clinician Rating (QIDS-C) and Self-Report (QIDS-SR): A psychometric evaluation in patients with chronic major depression. Biological Psychiatry. 2003; 54:573-583."
    }
